Hopefully I'm not being dismissive, but please look into terminology a bit better. I enjoy the content, but it'd be better with a little more research. Voltage and power are two different, but linked, things that have specific meanings. They are not interchangeable. Power is voltage*current. When dealing with battery cells you can put multiple cells in parallel to increase current output or in series to increase voltage. So both combos can increase power by increasing one variable while keeping the other constant (assuming all cells are identical). I would think no matter what you do to the potatoes, you'll still need a lot of them to drive a motor (even for a small toy tractor) because the power density is still very low compared to the min power the motor would need to operate. Anyway, thanks for the interesting video.
FYI, the size of the cables you use determines resistance so those alligator cables you used should be replaced with much thinner cables and connectors
Put anode and cathode closer. It reduces internal resistance. The DDP between zinc and copper should be 1.1V, but resistance is eating a lot of energy
